Belief in a divine author of the *laws* of nature aside, magic--"real" magic, as opposed to prestidigitation or Harry-Potter-style wizardry--was practiced under well-defined laws and mathematics. Only when those processes which, after scientific experimentation, would reliably "work" were distinguished from those which didn't, was Science separated from Magic; before then it was all one body of knowledge. Only then did astronomy separate from astrology, chemistry from alchemy, pharmacology from herbalism.

("laws" of nature/science, as opposed to "facts," seems to me an unfortunate choice of term, especially as we use the word "law" today.)

